│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash is a SIGSEGV occurring inside             │
│ SmallPtrSetImpl<llvm::SCEV const*>::insert during a traversal of SCEV         │
│ expressions triggered by ScalarEvolution::checkValidity via SCEVExprContains. │
│ The traversal routine SCEVTraversal::push unconditionally inserts the SCEV*   │
│ pointer into a SmallPtrSet and pushes it to the worklist, assuming it is      │
│ non-null. In this reproducer, the traversal is encountering a null SCEV       │
│ operand, leading to an attempt to insert a null pointer into SmallPtrSet,     │
│ which causes the segfault.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe provided logs show │
│ LV and SCEV analysis working through the minimal loop and invoking            │
│ ScalarEvolution::checkValidity inside getExistingSCEV, which calls            │
│ SCEVExprContains using SCEVTraversal::visitAll. The backtrace points directly │
│ into SCEVTraversal::push and SmallPtrSetImpl::insert, indicating the          │
│ insertion of the node being visited. No transformations have occurred yet;    │
│ this is purely analysis and validation. The repeated frames in                │
│ LoopVectorizationCostModel::shouldConsiderInvariant further corroborate that  │
│ the analysis is repeatedly querying SE for invariance and SCEV validity,      │
│ eventually encountering a pathological case.\n\n3. Root Cause                 │
│ Analysis:\nScalarEvolution::checkValidity uses SCEVExprContains to walk the   │
│ SCEV graph and identify invalid SCEVUnknowns (specifically those wrapping a   │
│ nullptr Value). However, SCEVTraversal::visitAll traverses operands of each   │
│ SCEV without guarding against null operands. If any SCEV node in the graph    │
│ has a null operand pointer (due to previous invalidation or construction      │
│ anomalies), SCEVTraversal::push will attempt to insert nullptr into the       │
│ SmallPtrSet and the worklist. SmallPtrSetImpl's insert does not accept        │
│ nullptr and will dereference assumptions leading to a segfault. The failing   │
│ code path is in SCEVTraversal::push at line 668: Visited.insert(S), where S   │
│ is nullptr.\n\nEven though checkValidity’s predicate specifically tests for   │
│ SCEVUnknown wrapping a null Value, the traversal crashes before it can make   │
│ that determination because it cannot safely traverse a null operand. In other │
│ words, checkValidity intends to be defensive, but the traversal itself is not │
│ defensive against null pointers.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe should     │
│ defensively guard SCEVTraversal::push against null SCEV pointers. This        │
│ ensures that validation and other analyses using SCEVTraversal won't crash    │
│ when encountering a null operand (whether due to invalidation or construction │
│ bugs elsewhere). This is a small, localized hardening change directly at the  │
│ crash point.\n\nEdit Point:\nFile:                                            │
│ llvm/include/llvm/Analysis/ScalarEvolutionExpressions.h\nLines:               │
│ 667-671\nChange: Add a null-check for the SCEV pointer in                     │
│ SCEVTraversal::push.\n\nCurrent code:\n  void push(const SCEV *S) {\n    if   │
│ (Visited.insert(S).second && Visitor.follow(S))\n                             │
│ Worklist.push_back(S);\n  }\n\nReplace with:\n  void push(const SCEV *S) {\n  │
│ if (!S)\n      return;\n    if (Visited.insert(S).second &&                   │
│ Visitor.follow(S))\n      Worklist.push_back(S);\n  }\n\nReasoning:\n-        │
│ Prevents insertion of null into SmallPtrSet and worklist.\n- Allows           │
│ checkValidity to continue evaluating other nodes and correctly flag invalid   │
│ SCEVs via its predicate, rather than crashing.\n- Minimal risk: skip-null     │
│ semantics are consistent with traversal intent; a null operand is not a valid │
│ SCEV node to visit.\n\nNOTICE (on assertion failure): Any assertion elsewhere │
│ that disallows null operands should still be considered a separate invariant  │
│ issue to investigate. This fix does not mask incorrect SCEV construction but  │
│ prevents the immediate crash and permits checkValidity to do its job.\n\n5.   │
│ Conclusion:\nThe crash stems from SCEVTraversal not handling null operands    │
│ defensively. By adding a simple null-check in SCEVTraversal::push, we avoid   │
│ inserting nullptr into SmallPtrSet and prevent the segfault during            │
│ ScalarEvolution::checkValidity. This hardening enables the existing validity  │
│ checks to function and will prevent similar crashes in other analyses that    │
│ rely on SCEVTraversal. The expected effect is that the reproducer no longer   │
│ crashes; instead, analyses proceed or report invalid SCEV as intended."})     │
